  <h2>Disasters of the Century: A Chronological Overview</h2>
  <p>The timeline below summarizes the earthquakes that profoundly affected Turkey over the past century and the shifts each one created in the country's disaster policies:</p>

  <div class="htl">
    <div class="htl-item major">
      <div class="htl-year">1939</div>
      <div class="htl-body">
        <div class="htl-tags"><span class="htl-tag mag">M 7.9</span><span class="htl-tag">Erzincan</span><span class="htl-tag">NAF</span></div>
        <h3>Erzincan Earthquake — The Deadliest Disaster of the Republic Era</h3>
        <p>On the night of December 27, a rupture at the eastern end of the North Anatolian Fault claimed approximately 33,000 lives and wiped Erzincan off the map. This disaster also marked the beginning of a westward-migrating earthquake sequence along the NAF: over the following 60 years the fault ruptured segment by segment toward the west like falling dominoes.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="htl-item">
      <div class="htl-year">1944</div>
      <div class="htl-body">
        <div class="htl-tags"><span class="htl-tag mag">M 7.2</span><span class="htl-tag">Bolu-Gerede</span></div>
        <h3>Bolu-Gerede and the Birth of Earthquake Regulations</h3>
        <p>Four major earthquakes on the NAF between 1939 and 1944 prompted the drafting of Turkey's first earthquake building code (1944) and first seismic hazard map (1945). The concept of "earthquake-resistant construction" entered legislation for the first time.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="htl-item major">
      <div class="htl-year">1999</div>
      <div class="htl-body">
        <div class="htl-tags"><span class="htl-tag mag">M 7.6</span><span class="htl-tag">Gölcük / İzmit</span><span class="htl-tag">NAF</span></div>
        <h3>Gölcük Earthquake — Turkey's Breaking Point</h3>
        <p>On August 17, 1999, at 03:02, a fault rupture in the eastern Marmara region claimed more than 17,000 lives by official figures; hundreds of thousands of buildings in the industrial heartland of Kocaeli and surrounding provinces were damaged. The Düzce earthquake (M 7.2) followed that November. These two disasters gave birth to mandatory earthquake insurance (DASK), the building inspection system, and modern search and rescue organization. Turkish earthquake awareness is divided into "before and after August 17."</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="htl-item">
      <div class="htl-year">2011</div>
      <div class="htl-body">
        <div class="htl-tags"><span class="htl-tag mag">M 7.1</span><span class="htl-tag">Van</span></div>
        <h3>Van Earthquake</h3>
        <p>The earthquake that struck the Van-Erciş corridor on October 23 claimed more than 600 lives. Buildings that collapsed during the aftershock period demonstrated in the most painful way possible how vital the rule "never return to a damaged building" truly is. The urban transformation law (Law No. 6306) was enacted in 2012, immediately following this earthquake.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="htl-item">
      <div class="htl-year">2020</div>
      <div class="htl-body">
        <div class="htl-tags"><span class="htl-tag mag">M 6.8</span><span class="htl-tag">Elazığ</span><span class="htl-tag mag">M 6.9</span><span class="htl-tag">İzmir-Samos</span></div>
        <h3>Elazığ and İzmir: Two Warning Earthquakes</h3>
        <p>In January the Elazığ-Sivrice earthquake struck (on the EAF), and in October the Aegean Sea-Samos earthquake caused widespread destruction in İzmir. Building collapses in Bayraklı — 70 km from the epicenter — due to soil amplification brought the <strong>decisive role of ground conditions in structural safety</strong> sharply into focus.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="htl-item major">
      <div class="htl-year">2023</div>
      <div class="htl-body">
        <div class="htl-tags"><span class="htl-tag mag">M 7.8</span><span class="htl-tag mag">M 7.6</span><span class="htl-tag">Kahramanmaraş</span><span class="htl-tag">EAF</span></div>
        <h3>Kahramanmaraş Earthquakes — The Disaster of the Century</h3>
        <p>On February 6, 2023, two earthquakes of magnitude 7.8 and 7.6 struck nine hours apart, rupturing approximately 500 kilometers of the East Anatolian Fault. Affecting 11 provinces and causing more than 50,000 deaths, this double earthquake is recorded as one of the largest continental earthquakes in modern measurement history. The oversight of building stock, construction amnesties, and the development of assembly areas were called into question — sharply and once again.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Three Major Lessons from This History</h2>

  <h3>1. Earthquakes repeat — fault memory is unfailing</h3>
  <p>The segments of the North Anatolian Fault that ruptured in 1939 proceeded to break westward in succession over the following 60 years: 1942 Niksar, 1943 Tosya, 1944 Gerede, 1957 Abant, 1967 Mudurnu, and finally 1999 Gölcük. This is precisely why scientists draw attention to the segment beneath the Marmara Sea. Seismic hazard is not a statistical abstraction — it is a cycle confirmed by a century of observation.</p>

  <h3>2. Building quality, not the earthquake, determines casualties</h3>
  <p>Earthquakes of similar magnitude produce vastly different outcomes depending on the building stock involved. Investigations into buildings that collapsed in the 1999 and 2023 disasters found unauthorized additional floors, severed load-bearing columns, and uninspected materials in a significant proportion. Turkey's earthquake history is also a history of <strong>building inspection</strong>: every major disaster pushed regulations a step forward — the 1944, 1975, 1998, 2007, and 2018 codes were all written in the shadow of great earthquakes.</p>

  <h3>3. Prepared communities change their fate</h3>
  <p>Countries with high seismic risk, like Japan and Chile, survive earthquakes of similar magnitude with far fewer casualties. The difference is not only engineering — it is regular drills, family disaster plans, and a culture of preparedness. You can find the first steps of individual preparedness in our <a href="/blog/deprem-cantasi-hayat-kurtarir.html">earthquake kit guide</a> and <a href="/blog/deprem-aninda-dogru-davranis.html">earthquake behavior guide</a>.</p>

